(678, 1, '2016-08-27 23:50:48', '2016-08-27 16:50:48', 'Laughter therapy\r\n<div>Instinctively, each parent we all know that laughter is the best remedy to solve a lot of problems happen to the child. Today, the scientists discovered that the humor seems to help young children learn many new things.</div><div><br /></div><div>Based on that knowledge to make children laugh out loud can help enhance the way of thinking, Rana Esseily, a French scientist and colleagues tested to discover whether the humor also impact the ability of the younger children learned or not.</div><div><br /></div><div>Each child 18 months will observe an adult use a device to try to grab a toy out of reach. In a group, adults will only play toy that after taking it ,, also in another group, after obtaining the adults will immediately threw the toy on the floor, making the children laugh, .</div><div><br /></div><div>When research data, the scientists discovered that the children had laughed to see the actions of adults are able to repeat the success of action than those who also see action, but not funny laughing, and even more successful than those who only see adults retrieve a toy a simple way, not amusing.</div><div><br /></div><div>&nbsp;</div><div><br /></div><div>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</div><div><br /></div><div>Why laughter is related to the child''s ability to learn has not been clearly shown, but the scientists offer two explanations are acceptable. The first possibility, which is due to temperament of each child, and not just because of the humor helps to learn better. The scientists explained that the kids happy, smiling tend associated with more ambient, while the others, and more interested in the successful implementation of a mission, just such as imitating adults regain toy.</div><div><br /></div><div>&nbsp;</div><div><br /></div><div>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</div><div><br /></div><div>Second hearing that the scientists made related to chemicals in the brain young. We all know that positive emotions such as laughter increases dopamine levels in the brain (a type of chemical that feel), and this is a positive impact on learning. "The effect was observed here can only be influenced by positive emotions in general and not specifically from laughter or humor," the scientists said.</div><div><br /></div><div>&nbsp;</div><div><br /></div><div>&nbsp;</div><div><br /></div><div>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</div><div><br /></div><div>Of course, we do not need to do more research on the impact of humor on learning, but as a longtime teacher, have experience with children of different ages, instinct always told me that the kids will enjoy fun, more interested in exploring and learning new things. The high level of interest of the child seems to be a guaranteed gold for holding and applying information and new understanding.</div><div><br /></div><div>So parents, let''s smile and support the learning of children, make sure that laughter always filled in your house. Enjoy the playful child, inquisitive of you discover the marvelous world around!</div><div><br /></div><div>&nbsp;</div><div><br /></div><div>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</div><div><br /></div><div>Dr Trevor</div><div><br /></div><div>Source: According to the Journal of Cognition and Emotion The.</div>', 'Laughter therapy', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'laughter-therapy', '', '', '2016-08-27 23:50:48', '2016-08-27 16:50:48', '', 0, 'http://localhost/html/?p=678', 0, 'post', '', 0),
